Plaintext password comparison
In AdminLogin.jsx, the login query selects a worker by matching both username and password directly from the database — meaning passwords are stored in plaintext. This is a serious security vulnerability. Passwords must be hashed (e.g. bcrypt) and compared server-side, ideally via a Supabase Edge Function or RPC, never from the client.

■
API key exposed in source code
The Supabase URL and anon key in supabaseClient.js are committed directly into the code. While the anon key is meant to be public, it should still live in a .env file (VITE_SUPABASE_URL, VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY) so it's excluded from version control and easier to rotate.

Should fix
■
Translation objects duplicated in three files
AdminLogin.jsx, Dashboard.jsx, and App.jsx each define their own inline t = { en, fr, ar } object instead of using the shared translations.js module you already have. Consolidate everything into translations.js and import it everywhere.

■
TicketForm has too many useState calls
TicketForm.jsx manages 15+ separate state variables. Group related state into objects — for example, combine location, exactLocation, problemType, priority, description, availability into a single formState object. This makes resets and validation much cleaner.

■
Priority lookup is language-dependent
In utils.js, assignPriority() matches against translated strings (French, Arabic, English versions of "Electricity" etc.). If the locale changes, lookups break silently. Instead, assign priority based on a language-neutral key (e.g. 'electricity') and translate only for display.

■
Debug console.log statements left in production
AdminLogin.jsx has three console.log calls that log the username, password query result, and job title. These should be removed before deploying — they expose user data in the browser console.

